{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535887"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15556"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15556"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.03,0.11,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76131"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4738"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about investigation for endometriosis. She describes a three-year history of intermittent right flank pain, which has been treated as urinary tract infections multiple times with variable response to antibiotics. She reports progressive dysmenorrhoea and deep dyspareunia. Her periods are regular but heavy, lasting seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe had previously been trying to conceive again for 18 months without success, but decided to put family planning on hold at this stage. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the right iliac fossa without guarding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transvaginal ultrasound","Trial of medroxyprogesterone acetate depot","Trial of combined oral contraceptive pill","Diagnostic cystoscopy","Immediate referral for laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with several features suggestive of endometriosis: chronic pelvic pain, dysmenorrhoea, dyspareunia, and subfertility. The cyclical nature of symptoms and their association with menstruation increases the clinical suspicion. While laparoscopy remains the gold standard for diagnosis, appropriate initial investigation is essential before commencing treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. It allows for exclusion of other pathologies that may mimic endometriosis symptoms, such as ovarian cysts, fibroids, or adenomyosis. While ultrasound cannot reliably diagnose all forms of endometriosis (particularly superficial peritoneal disease), it can identify endometriomas, deep infiltrating endometriosis, and pouch of Douglas obliteration. Given this patient\u0027s right iliac fossa tenderness and history of right flank pain, imaging is particularly important to exclude other causes of pain such as renal pathology. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial of combined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable management option but should follow appropriate investigation. While hormonal therapy can provide symptomatic relief and is often used empirically, initiating treatment without baseline imaging may delay diagnosis of other conditions or significant endometriosis requiring surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial of medroxyprogesterone acetate depot\u003C/strong\u003E is less suitable as first-line therapy. While effective for some patients, continuous progestogen therapy alone is generally less effective than combined hormonal contraception for endometriosis-related pain. Additionally, its long-acting nature makes it difficult to reverse if side effects occur or if fertility becomes a priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic cystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there were specific urinary symptoms suggesting bladder wall involvement. While the patient has had recurrent urinary symptoms, these are more likely related to endometriosis affecting surrounding structures or cyclic inflammation rather than bladder wall involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate referral for laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the first step. While it remains the gold standard for diagnosis, it is invasive and should be reserved for cases where conservative management fails or when definitive diagnosis is essential for treatment planning. The risks of surgery must be weighed against the potential benefits, particularly when empiric medical therapy may provide symptom relief following appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transvaginal ultrasound is an important initial investigation in suspected endometriosis to exclude other pathologies and identify features such as endometriomas.","Endometriosis should be considered in women with chronic pelvic pain, particularly when symptoms are cyclical or associated with menstruation.","A thorough menstrual, pain, and fertility history is essential in the initial assessment of suspected endometriosis."],"references":["Kalaitzopoulos DR, Samartzis N, Kolovos GN, Mareti E, Samartzis EP, Eberhard M, Dinas K, Daniilidis A. Treatment of endometriosis: a review with comparison of 8 guidelines. BMC women\u0027s health. 2021 Dec;21:1-9. Available online at ; https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1186/s12905-021-01545-5.pdf","Malvezzi H, Marengo EB, Podgaec S, Piccinato CA. Endometriosis: current challenges in modeling a multifactorial disease of unknown etiology. J Transl Med. 2020 Aug 12;18(1):311. doi: 10.1186/s12967-020-02471-0. PMID: 32787880; PMCID: PMC7425005. Available online at ; https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1186/s12967-020-02471-0.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76131"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15556"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76131"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T10:28:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T11:40:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attribut